stand for classical and quantum probabilities, respectively [45]. Therefore, there is a bijective correspondence between $\mu $ and ${\epsilon }^{\mu }$ and in consequence,  the probability measure is effectively replaced with the collection of truth values [45]. 

 But, it is known that, each context $V\in \mathcal{V}(\mathcal{H})$ can be generated from a set of pairwise orthogonal projections $\{P_1,P_2,\cdots ,P_k\}$. Therefore, based on the above descriptions, $({\mu }_{\vert V}\left(P_1\right),\ {\mu }_{\vert V}\left(P_2\right),\ \cdots ,\ {\mu }_{\vert V}\left(P_k\right))$ is the probability distribution. Hence to each context $V$ we can assign the Shannon entropy of its associated probability distribution [63]
